SpNote.title: About This Library
SpNote.note:
CONTENTS
This library contains bright G-type stars accessible to UKIRT, between 3rd and 7th magnitude in the V band.
For standard star long-slit spectroscopy an east-west slit (P.A. = -90 degrees) and a nod of 12.0 arcseconds (100 pixels) is recommended, so that the star lands (is centred) on two rows. For IFU observations nodding to blank sky is recommended, though in good seeing it may be possible to nod the star between the top and bottom half of the IFU field-of-view.
USING THE LIBRARY
To use this library, identify (from the object name, which includes the RA and Dec) the star you want to observe, and drag the target component from the library window into your science programme, i.e. replace the target component in the "standard star" observation in your spectroscopy or IFU MSB.
CAVEATS
From the target magnitude listed in the component name, a rough exposure time may be entered in your observation using the pull-down source-magnitude menu. In good seeing conditions, however, this estimate may be too long (i.e. you may saturate on the star); in bad seeing or cirrusy conditions you may need to increase the exposure times to get sufficient signal on the array. Also, you may wish to increase the number of times a quad is repeated to get better signal/noise.
IMPORTANT!
The UIST component (grism, slit width and slit p.a.) must be the same for flat/arc, standard star and science target observations.
